To decrypt the message using the Hill cipher, we first need to find the inverse of the key matrix. The key matrix is:
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 2 \\
3 & 5
\end{pmatrix}
$$

To find the inverse, we first calculate the determinant of the matrix:
$$
\text{det} = (1)(5) - (2)(3) = 5 - 6 = -1
$$

Since we are working with modulo 26 (the number of letters in the alphabet), we need to find the modular inverse of the determinant. The modular inverse of -1 (mod 26) is 25, because (-1)(25) = -25 â‰¡ 1 (mod 26).

Now we can find the adjugate of the matrix and multiply it by the modular inverse of the determinant:

$$
\text{adjugate} = 
\begin{pmatrix}
5 & -2 \\
-3 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
$$

$$
\text{inverse} = 25 \times \text{adjugate} \pmod{26} =
\begin{pmatrix}
5 & 24 \\
23 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
$$

Now we can decrypt the message by multiplying the inverse matrix by each ciphertext vector:

$$
\begin{pmatrix}
5 & 24 \\
23 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
15 \\
3
\end{pmatrix}
\pmod{26} =
\begin{pmatrix}
3 \\
0
\end{pmatrix}
$$

$$
\begin{pmatrix}
5 & 24 \\
23 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
6 \\
0
\end{pmatrix}
\pmod{26} =
\begin{pmatrix}
2 \\
18
\end{pmatrix}
$$

$$
\begin{pmatrix}
5 & 24 \\
23 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
0 \\
14
\end{pmatrix}
\pmod{26} =
\begin{pmatrix}
8 \\
14
\end{pmatrix}
$$

$$
\begin{pmatrix}
5 & 24 \\
23 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
5 \\
1
\end{pmatrix}
\pmod{26} =
\begin{pmatrix}
1 \\
4
\end{pmatrix}
$$

Now we convert the numerical values back to letters (A=0, B=1, ..., Z=25):

$$
\begin{pmatrix}
3 \\
0
\end{pmatrix} = \text{D A},
\begin{pmatrix}
2 \\
18
\end{pmatrix} = \text{C S},
\begin{pmatrix}
8 \\
14
\end{pmatrix} = \text{I O},
\begin{pmatrix}
1 \\
4
\end{pmatrix} = \text{B E}
$$

So the decrypted message is "DACSIOBE".
